Process Bay Cases

Derek Ouyang

4/14/2020

The following makes use of new Bay Area city-level curation from LA Times. See Github repo.

library(tidyverse)
library(mapview)
library(sf)
library(tigris)
library(leaflet)
library(plotly)

options(
  tigris_class = "sf"
)

Load full LA Times data and filter to Bay Area counties. Unlike load_covid19_cases, here were directly grabbing a public CSV file from its Github URL.

ca_city_cases <- 
  read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/datadesk/california-coronavirus-data/master/latimes-place-totals.csv")

bay_county_names <-
  c(
    "Alameda",
    "Contra Costa",
    "Marin",
    "Napa",
    "San Francisco",
    "San Mateo",
    "Santa Clara",
    "Solano",
    "Sonoma"
  )

bay_counties <- 
  counties("CA", cb=F, progress_bar=F) %>% 
  filter(NAME %in% bay_county_names)

bay_city_cases <-
  ca_city_cases %>% 
  filter(county %in% bay_county_names)

Counties included:

bay_city_cases %>% 
  pull(county) %>% 
  unique()
## [1] "Alameda"      "Contra Costa" "Santa Clara"  "Sonoma"

Upon inspecting the data, there are some place designations that are unique, like jails, homeless population, etc that will need to be dealt with specially for mapping. Lets first see how they map with the lat/long data theyve documented. There are some places without coordinates.

bay_city_cases %>% 
  filter(is.na(x)) %>% 
  pull(place) %>% 
  unique()
## [1] "Unincorporated"               "Alameda County LHJ"          
## [3] "Berkeley LHJ"                 "Known Homeless"              
## [5] "No Address (May Be Homeless)" "Other/Unspecified"           
## [7] "Other/Unknown"

Mapping others, basic view:

bay_city_cases %>% 
  filter(!is.na(x)) %>% 
  filter(date == max(date)) %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("x","y")) %>% 
  st_set_crs(4326) %>% 
  mapview(
    cex = "confirmed_cases",
    zcol = "confirmed_cases",
    at = c(0,25,50,100,250,500,1000,2000)
  ) + 
  mapview(
    bay_counties %>% 
      filter(NAME %in% (bay_city_cases %>% pull(county) %>% unique())),
    alpha.region = 0,
    legend = F
  )

Get a list of places that are mappable but dont have a direct match with Census places (tigris).

bay_places <- 
  places("CA",cb=F,progress_bar=F) %>% 
  st_centroid() %>% 
  st_join(bay_counties, left=F) %>% 
  dplyr::select(NAME = NAME.x) %>% 
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>% 
  left_join(places("CA",cb=F,progress_bar=F)) %>% 
  st_as_sf()

bay_city_cases %>%
  filter(!is.na(x)) %>% 
  filter(!place %in% bay_places$NAME) %>% 
  pull(place) %>% 
  unique()
## [1] "Santa Rita Jail" "Central County"  "East County"     "North County"   
## [5] "South County"    "West County"

And where they are on the map (using the most recent date of cases):

bay_city_cases %>% 
  filter(!is.na(x)) %>% 
  filter(!place %in% bay_places$NAME) %>% 
  filter(date == max(date)) %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("x","y")) %>% 
  st_set_crs(4326) %>% 
  mapview(
    cex = "confirmed_cases",
    zcol = "confirmed_cases",
    at = c(0,25,50,100,250,500,1000,2000)
  ) + 
  mapview(
    bay_counties %>% 
      filter(NAME %in% (bay_city_cases %>% pull(county) %>% unique())),
    alpha.region = 0,
    legend = F
  )

Looks like the County places are unique subsets for Sonoma County, and otherwise Santa Rita Jail is the one jail explicitly documented in Alameda County.

For the purposes of the rest of the exercise, well focus on Santa Clara County.

List of unique places:

scc_city_cases <-
  bay_city_cases %>% 
  filter(county == "Santa Clara")

scc_city_cases %>% 
  pull(place) %>% 
  unique()
##  [1] "Campbell"        "Cupertino"       "Gilroy"          "Los Altos"      
##  [5] "Los Altos Hills" "Los Gatos"       "Milpitas"        "Monte Sereno"   
##  [9] "Morgan Hill"     "Mountain View"   "Other/Unknown"   "Palo Alto"      
## [13] "San Jose"        "Santa Clara"     "Saratoga"        "Sunnyvale"      
## [17] "Unincorporated"

Looking at the data itself, Unincorporated is only logged on the first day of data and has < 10 cases, and then it seems like Other/Unknown is the standard category for all other cases. So well remove the original Unincorporated observation and track Other/Unknown moving forward, which will be mapped as a random point on the unincorporated portion of the map.

Also, any case count logged as a number less than 10 should actually only be identified as < 10 per the original source.

scc_city_cases_cleaned <-
  scc_city_cases %>% 
  filter(place != "Unincorporated") %>% 
  mutate(
    confirmed_cases =
      ifelse(
        confirmed_cases < 10,
        NA,
        confirmed_cases
      )
  )

Prepping the geometries, especially the unincorporated area which will be all the portions of SCC that arent official places.

scc_county <- 
  bay_counties %>% 
  filter(NAME == "Santa Clara") %>% 
  dplyr::select(NAME)

# Note that Mountain View is duplicated in the original data
scc_places <- 
  bay_places %>% 
  st_join(scc_county, left=F) %>% 
  dplyr::select(NAME = NAME.x) %>% 
  filter(!duplicated(NAME))

scc_unincorporated <- 
  scc_county %>% 
  st_difference(st_union(scc_places)) %>% 
  mutate(
    NAME = "Other/Unknown"
  )

scc_places_full <-
  rbind(scc_places,scc_unincorporated) %>% 
  dplyr::select(NAME) %>% 
  st_transform(4326)

mapview(scc_unincorporated)+
  mapview(c(-121.59,37.35) %>% st_point() %>% st_sfc() %>% st_sf() %>% st_set_crs(4326))

Ive added an arbitrary point above that is clearly within the unincorporated region and will be distinct from the city points.

Now, bringing it all together in a final map. Im switching from mapview to leaflet which provides more customizatability (see tutorial here).

scc_city_cases_final <-
  scc_city_cases_cleaned %>% 
  mutate(
    x = 
      ifelse(
        is.na(x),
        -121.59,
        x
      ),
    y =
      ifelse(
        is.na(y),
        37.35,
        y
      ),
  ) %>% 
  left_join(
    scc_places_full,
    by = c("place" = "NAME")
  ) %>%  
  st_as_sf() %>% 
  st_set_crs(4326) %>% 
  mutate(
    case_density = (confirmed_cases/st_area(.)*2.59e6) %>% as.numeric() # cases per square mile. The conversion is from sq meters to sq miles.
  ) %>% 
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%  # Reduces the size of the data frame by removing the polygon information. This is better stored inside of scc_places_full and joined for a given slice of time.
  as.data.frame()

# This is a way to set up a color range to be used later. See https://rstudio.github.io/leaflet/colors.html.
blue_pal <- colorNumeric(
  palette = "Blues",
  domain = 
    c(0,scc_city_cases_final %>% 
    pull(case_density) %>% 
    unique())
)

map <- leaflet(
    data =
      scc_city_cases_final %>% 
        filter(date == max(date))
  ) %>% 
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% # You can pick a lot of different basemap options: see https://rstudio.github.io/leaflet/basemaps.html
  addPolygons(
    data = 
      scc_city_cases_final %>% 
        filter(date == max(date)) %>% 
      left_join(scc_places_full, by = c("place"="NAME")) %>% 
      st_as_sf(),
    fillColor = ~blue_pal(case_density),
    color = "white",
    weight = 0.25,
    fillOpacity = 0.5,
    label = ~paste0(case_density %>% round(1)," cases per sq.mi."),
    highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
      weight = 2,
      opacity = 1
    )
  ) %>%
  addCircles(
    lng = ~x,
    lat = ~y,
    color = "blue",
    weight = 0.25,
    radius = ~sqrt(confirmed_cases)*100,
    fillOpacity = 0.5,
    label = ~paste0(place,": ",confirmed_cases," cases"),
    highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
      weight = 2,
      opacity = 1
    )
  ) %>% 
  addPolygons(
    data = scc_county %>% st_transform(4326),
    fill = F,
    weight = 1,
    color = "gray"
  )

map
